# Karpathy Coding Discipline

## Four Principles (blocking — all must be satisfied)

### 1. Think Before Coding
- State assumptions explicitly before writing code
- If uncertain about requirements, architecture, or side effects — **ask**
- Never guess at business logic; confirm from context or user

### 2. Simplicity First
- Start with the minimum viable solution
- No speculative features, premature abstractions, or "might need later" code
- Escalate complexity only when the simple approach demonstrably fails
- One function should do one thing

### 3. Surgical Changes
- Only touch files and code directly related to the current request
- Do not refactor, rename, or reorganize unless explicitly asked
- Leave unrelated code better than you found it only if it is in the same function/block

### 4. Goal-Driven Execution
- Define success criteria before implementation
- Verify the change works (run it, test it, check the output)
- Loop until success criteria are met — do not declare "done" without verification

## Pre-Emit Review (before every code output)

- [ ] Assumptions stated? If not, state them now.
- [ ] Is this the simplest solution? Could it be simpler?
- [ ] Am I touching only what the request requires?
- [ ] How will I verify this works? State the verification step.
- [ ] No breaking changes to existing functionality?
- [ ] Types correct, no `any` without justification?
